	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I was just saying that "IF this THEN do that" is much easier for someone with no computer architecture knowledge to understand than compares, flags, branches and jumps, because the former is just plain old english.
<br />
<br />I mean, going from english to assembly can be a bit to harsh, while english -&gt; high level language -&gt; assembly might be easier to do, because the middle step serves as a sort of connector. At the same time the person is learning how to tell a computer what to do with simple english-like structures, they are learning about programming concepts that will be useful at a lower level.
<br />
<br />I never said that diving directly into assembly was impossible, though. People like you and Memblers have proved this is possible. I just think it can be harder (not that it will be so for everyone).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


