		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I mean, going from english to assembly can be a bit to harsh, while english -&gt; high level language -&gt; assembly might be easier to do, because the middle step serves as a sort of connector. At the same time the person is learning how to tell a computer what to do with simple english-like structures, they are learning about programming concepts that will be useful at a lower level.</div><br />It might be even better if your first high-level language looks like English. Early on in my job, I wrote what my boss thought was pseudocode. I double-clicked it, and he was surprised when it actually ran. It was Python.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">there is a "pow()" function </div>
<br />That's fine for floats. If you need one for ints, you can roll your own function to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation_by_squaring" class="postlink">square and multiply</a>, and then just stick it in your personal library.
<br />
<br />Thanks Fx3 for suggesting a split point.

		

